Amazon CloudWatch is AWS’s native monitoring and observability service that collects metrics, logs, and traces from your cloud resources and applications, helping you detect issues, set alarms, and visualize performance in real time. It’s essential for tracking system health, troubleshooting, and automating responses to infrastructure or application changes.

🌐 Key Features of AWS CloudWatch
📊 Metrics & Dashboards
Metrics: Automatically collects data from AWS services (EC2, RDS, Lambda, etc.) and supports custom metrics via API or CloudWatch Agent.

Dashboards: Unified, customizable views of metrics and logs. Can be shared across accounts and regions.

Automatic dashboards: Prebuilt for many AWS services to reduce setup effort.

🔔 Alarms & Automated Actions
Alarms: Monitor metrics against thresholds (e.g., CPU > 80%).

Actions: Trigger notifications (SNS), auto-scaling, or automated remediation when thresholds are breached.

Composite alarms: Combine multiple alarms for complex monitoring scenarios.

📜 Logs & Insights
CloudWatch Logs: Collect and store logs from AWS services, applications, and on-premises systems.

Logs Insights: Query logs with a powerful SQL-like language for troubleshooting.

Log classes:

Standard (frequent access)

Infrequent Access (Logs-IA) (cost-optimized for rarely accessed logs)

⚙️ Application & Infrastructure Monitoring
Application Signals: Auto-detect latency, error rates, and request rates without manual instrumentation.

CloudWatch Synthetics: Simulate user behavior with “canaries” to proactively test endpoints and APIs.

CloudWatch RUM (Real User Monitoring): Collects performance data from real user sessions.

Database Insights: Monitor query performance and troubleshoot load issues.

Container & Lambda Insights: Specialized monitoring for ECS, EKS, and AWS Lambda.

🔄 Advanced Capabilities
Cross-account observability: Monitor applications spanning multiple AWS accounts.

OpenTelemetry support: Integrates with open-source observability tools like Prometheus and Grafana.

Metric Streams: Continuously stream metrics to external destinations (e.g., Kinesis, data lakes).

AI-powered anomaly detection: Automatically identifies unusual patterns in metrics.

